This falls under the domain of computational engineering, making cs.CE the most likely category.
- cs.MS (Mathematical Software): The paper describes the development of a software framework for simulation of flow and transport in fractured reservoirs, which involves mathematical modeling and numerical methods. This makes cs.MS a likely category.
- cs.NA (Numerical Analysis): The paper involves the development of numerical methods for simulation of flow and transport in fractured reservoirs, as well as deformation of the reservoir due to shearing along fracture and fault planes. This makes cs.NA a likely category.
- cs.RO (Robotics): This category is less likely, but the paper does mention the use of PorePy for modeling rock mechanics and poro-elasticity, which could potentially be applied in the field of robotics for modeling deformable materials.
- cs.SE (Software Engineering): This category is also less likely, but the paper does describe the development of an open-source software framework, which involves software engineering principles such as modular design, testing, and documentation.
